    <section id="warnings">
      <h2>Warnings</h2>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Expecting Linear Results From an Exponential Process">
        Most people abandon compounding strategies during the "valley of disappointment" — the early period when effort is high and visible results are low. They mistakenly apply linear expectations to an exponential process. Understanding this gap intellectually, and committing to your inputs independent of early results, is essential for getting to the exponential phase.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Spreading Compounding Too Thin">
        Trying to compound ten different habits simultaneously almost always produces worse results than focusing on two or three. Attention and willpower are finite resources. Spreading them across too many domains prevents any single area from reaching the momentum threshold where compounding feels self-sustaining. Depth of compounding beats breadth.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title={`Warning: Mistaking "Busy" for "Compounding"`}>
        Activity is not the same as compounding inputs. You can be extremely busy with tasks that produce zero compound returns — managing a full inbox, attending unproductive meetings, consuming news. Compounding requires that your inputs build on previous inputs. If you cannot trace a clear line from today's action to a better future version of yourself, that action is not compounding.
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

    <section id="faq">
